Row filters. Where a column mask controls which columns' values you see, a row filter controls which rows you see at all. It's a function that returns a boolean per row, and Unity Catalog adds an implicit WHERE clause on every read, keeping only the rows where that function returns true for the querying principal.

Look at the example. Region-filter takes a country and returns a boolean. If you're in the compliance-i-n group, it returns true only where country equals I-N. If you're in compliance-u-s, only where country equals U-S. If you're in the broad compliance group, it returns true for everything. And otherwise, it returns false. Then you attach it with alter-table, set-row-filter, on the country column.

From then on, every select from silver-dot-customers is implicitly WHERE region-filter of country equals true. Each principal sees only their own slice of rows. And note the default: a member of none of those groups hits the else-false branch and sees nothing at all — zero rows. That's a safe default.

To remove it, you alter-table drop-row-filter.

Now, the powerful part is combining the two. Column mask plus row filter equals the bank's full P-I-I regime. A compliance analyst in India sees full P-I-I — but only for Indian customers' rows. A plain analyst sees only the Indian rows and gets REDACTED in the P-A-N column. So masks decide which columns' values you see; row filters decide which rows you see. Put them together on one base table, and you have true column-and-row-level security — enforced everywhere, for every reader, without a secure view in sight.
